<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF9EFFCF64B3FA275C27FFBC" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64B3FA275A0DFF04" blockId="6.[151,1436,547,645]" box="[151,812,547,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
<materialsCitation id="3B4C3CF3FF9EFFCF64B3FA275A09FF04" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3763101311" box="[151,808,547,573]" collectionCode="LOCALITY" country="Namibia" location="Mahongo" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Kavango West" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus id="549F880CFF9EFFCF64B3FA2759FCFF04" box="[151,221,547,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">TYPE</typeStatus>
<collectionCode id="ED35AE6BFF9EFFCF64C0FA275853FF04" box="[228,370,547,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">LOCALITY</collectionCode>
: 
<location id="8EFB6075FF9EFFCF6558FA2758CBFF04" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:038D87B8FF9EFFCF64B3F9DE582FF834:8EFB6075FF9EFFCF6558FA2758CBFF04" box="[380,490,547,573]" country="Namibia" name="Mahongo" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" stateProvince="Kavango West">Mahongo</location>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49E0F84CFF9EFFCF65D2FA275B98FF04" box="[502,697,547,573]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Kavango District</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF66E0FA275A09FF04" box="[708,808,547,573]" name="Namibia" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Namibia</collectingCountry>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FA435C27FFBC" blockId="6.[151,1436,547,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
Described and named as a new species based on morphological characters of the adults, larva and pupa, and differences in chromosomal inversion banding patterns compared with 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF9EFFCF6790FA6F5C20FFBC" authority="Grunberg, 1902" authorityName="Grunberg" authorityYear="1902" box="[948,1281,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ziemanni">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF6790FA6F5D66FFBD" box="[948,1095,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">An. ziemanni</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF606AFA6F5C20FFBC" author="Grunberg, K." box="[1102,1281,619,645]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="550 - 551" refId="ref8747" refString="Grunberg, K. (1902) Ein neuer Anopheles aus Westafrika, Anopheles ziemanni nov. spec. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 25 (677), 550 - 551." type="journal article" year="1902">Grünberg, 1902</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF9EFFCF64B3FAB75CAEF998" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64B3FAB7587EFFF4" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" box="[151,351,691,717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">DESCRIPTION:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FAD358E7FFC8" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" box="[199,454,726,753]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64E3FAD35875FFC8" box="[199,340,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Wing length</emphasis>
: 5.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FAFF588FFE01" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64E3FAFF5827FE2D" box="[199,262,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF9EFFCF6531FAFF587CFE2C" box="[277,349,762,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1690,1714]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,1325,1658]" captionTargetId="figure-347@6.[151,1436,1317,1667]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anopheles namibiensis: wing (from Coetzee 1984)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521616" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521616/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
): Subcostal and preapical pale spots present, small; apical pale fringe spot rarely extending beyond wing tip of R 
<subScript id="17A034EBFF9EFFCF65B9FB355887FE06" attach="left" box="[413,422,817,831]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">3</subScript>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FB475A2EFE64" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" box="[199,783,835,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64E3FB4758B1FE64" box="[199,400,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Maxillary palpus</emphasis>
: Shaggy, with four pale bands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FB635A1BFEF0" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64E3FB635820FEB9" box="[199,257,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Legs</emphasis>
:Apex of foretibia and base of foretarsomere 1 always dark. Apex of hindtibia, base of hindtarsomere 1 and apices of hindtarsomeres 1 and 2 with pale spots at most 3 times as wide as diameter of the tarsomere; hindtarsomeres 4 and 5 pale, 0.5 of hindtarsomere 3 pale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FBD758B5F928" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
LARVAL HABITAT: Vegetated pools and swamps in forested areas around Yaoundé, 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF6138FBD75CBDFED4" box="[1308,1436,979,1005]" name="Cameroon" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF6484FBF358A7F928" author="Manga, L. &amp; Mbingue, S. &amp; Nkou Etoundi, M. &amp; Ngollo, M." box="[160,390,1015,1041]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="409" refId="ref9927" refString="Manga, L., Mbingue, S., Nkou Etoundi, M. &amp; Ngollo, M. (1997) Anopheles namibiensis is anthropophilic and widespread in Cameroon. Medical and Veterinary Entomology, 11 (4), 409. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2915.1997. tb 00432. x" type="journal article" year="1997">
Manga 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64DBFBF3581DF928" box="[255,316,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">et al.</emphasis>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FC1F5CAEF998" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
ADULT BIOLOGY: Females were collected in cattle enclosures at the 
<typeStatus id="549F880CFF9EFFCF6005FC1F5D70F90C" box="[1057,1105,1051,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF60E2FC1F5C4AF90C" author="Coetzee, M." box="[1222,1387,1051,1077]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref7634" refString="Coetzee, M. (1984) A new species of Anopheles (Anopheles) from Namibia (Diptera: Culicidae). Systematic Entomology, 9 (1), 1 - 8. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.1984. tb 00498. x" type="journal article" year="1984">Coetzee 1984</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF64B3FC3B582EF960" box="[151,271,1087,1113]" name="Cameroon" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, human landing catches carried out in Simbock village, Yaoundé, yielded 10 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF9EFFCF60A3FC3B583DF944" authority="(Manga et al. 1997)" baseAuthorityName="Manga" baseAuthorityYear="1997" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namibiensis">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF60A3FC3B5C1DF960" box="[1159,1340,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">An. namibiensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF6169FC3B5835F944" author="Manga, L. &amp; Mbingue, S. &amp; Nkou Etoundi, M. &amp; Ngollo, M." pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="409" refId="ref9927" refString="Manga, L., Mbingue, S., Nkou Etoundi, M. &amp; Ngollo, M. (1997) Anopheles namibiensis is anthropophilic and widespread in Cameroon. Medical and Veterinary Entomology, 11 (4), 409. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2915.1997. tb 00432. x" type="journal article" year="1997">
Manga 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF64B3FC6759F1F944" box="[151,208,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">et al.</emphasis>
1997
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The records of 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF9EFFCF65F1FC675BA8F944" box="[469,649,1123,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="namibiensis">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF65F1FC675BA8F944" box="[469,649,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">An. namibiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF66EBFC675A65F944" box="[719,836,1123,1149]" name="Cameroon" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF6776FC675D36F944" author="Ayala, D. &amp; Costantini, C. &amp; Ose, K. &amp; Kamdem, G. C. &amp; Antonio-Nkondjio, C. &amp; Agbor, J-P. &amp; Awono-Ambene, P. &amp; Fontenille, D. &amp; Simard, F." box="[850,1047,1123,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="307" refId="ref6827" refString="Ayala, D., Costantini, C., Ose, K., Kamdem, G. C., Antonio-Nkondjio, C., Agbor, J-P., Awono-Ambene, P., Fontenille, D. &amp; Simard, F. (2009) Habitat suitability and ecological niche profile of major malaria vectors in Cameroon. Malaria Journal, 8, 307. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / 1475 - 2875 - 8 - 307" type="journal article" year="2009">
Ayala 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF67B9FC675AF7F944" box="[925,982,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
) using pyrethrum spray catches in houses show it to be present in the western highlands, 
<collectingRegion id="49E0F84CFF9EFFCF66D3FC835A51F998" box="[759,880,1159,1185]" country="Cameroon" name="Adamaoua" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Adamaoua</collectingRegion>
highlands and the central plateau near Yaoundé.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF9EFFCF64E3FCAF582FF834" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF9EFFCF64E3FCAF582FF834" blockId="6.[151,1437,691,1293]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">
DISTRIBUTION: Mahongo in 
<collectingRegion id="49E0F84CFF9EFFCF667CFCAF5A18F9FC" box="[600,825,1195,1221]" country="Namibia" name="Kavango West" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Kavango District</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF67EDFCAF5D16F9FC" box="[969,1079,1195,1221]" name="Namibia" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Namibia</collectingCountry>
; Yaoundé, 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF60F7FCAF5C76F9FC" box="[1235,1367,1195,1221]" name="Cameroon" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
. The Tanzanian distribution record given in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF9EFFCF66A3FCCB5A4BF9D0" author="Irish, S. R. &amp; Kyalo, D. &amp; Snow, R. W. &amp; Coetzee, M." box="[647,874,1231,1257]" pageId="6" pageNumber="188" pagination="401 - 449" refId="ref9235" refString="Irish, S. R., Kyalo, D., Snow, R. W. &amp; Coetzee, M. (2020) Updated list of Anopheles species (Diptera: Culicidae) by country in the Afrotropical Region and associated islands. Zootaxa, 4747 (3), 401 - 449. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4747.3.1" type="journal article" year="2020">
Irish 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF9EFFCF66EFFCCB5A2DF9D0" box="[715,780,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">et al.</emphasis>
(2020)
</bibRefCitation>
is incorrect as Mahongo is in 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF60DCFCCB5C44F9D0" box="[1272,1381,1231,1257]" name="Namibia" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, not 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF9EFFCF64B3FCF7582BF834" box="[151,266,1267,1293]" name="Tanzania" pageId="6" pageNumber="188">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
